  "prompt": "Is it too late to start a computer science degree if I am 20 and don't know any programming languages?",
  "response": "It's definitely not too late to start a computer science degree at 20, and not knowing any programming languages is not a barrier to entry. Many students begin their studies without prior programming experience. Computer science programs generally start with introductory courses that teach the fundamentals of programming, algorithms, and computer systems.\n\nHere are some points to consider:\n\n1. **Introductory Courses:** Most universities have intro courses in programming, often designed for beginners. These courses will teach you the basic concepts and help you build a solid foundation.\n\n2. **Resources Available:** There are plenty of online resources, tutorials, and courses available (such as Codecademy, freeCodeCamp, Coursera, and edX) that can help you learn programming languages before you start your degree or parallel to your studies.\n\n3. **Age is Not a Barrier:** Many students in computer science programs come from diverse backgrounds, and there is no age limit on learning. People of all ages are pursuing degrees and changing careers, so you\u2019ll be in good company.\n\n4. **Career Opportunities:** A degree in computer science can lead to a wide array of career opportunities in technology, which is a rapidly growing field. The skills you learn will be in demand regardless of your starting point.\n\n5. **Soft Skills Matter:** In addition to technical skills, soft skills such as problem-solving, collaboration, and communication are also vital in tech fields and can be developed alongside your technical knowledge.\n\nIf you enjoy problem-solving and are interested in technology, pursuing a computer science degree can be a great choice for your future!",
